# Django Documentation & Changelog Enforcement Rule

## Phase Gate — Precondition Check

**This phase MUST NOT execute until ALL of the following are confirmed:**

- [ ] Feature implementation is complete
- [ ] 3 audit iterations have been performed and resolved
- [ ] All related tests have been written
- [ ] Coverage thresholds are met and enforced

If any precondition is unmet → **stop and complete the missing phase first**.

Only after all boxes above are checked does this documentation phase begin.

---

## Step 1 — Documentation Scan & Update

### 1.1 Scan the `/docs` Directory

Before writing anything, scan the full `/docs` directory tree:

```
/docs/
  api/
  architecture/
  services/
  permissions/
  models/
  flows/
  changes/
```

Identify every documentation file that is impacted by the current change. Ask:

- Does this change touch an **API endpoint**? → Update `/docs/api/`
- Does this change modify **business logic**? → Update `/docs/services/` or `/docs/flows/`
- Does this change affect **permissions or access control**? → Update `/docs/permissions/`
- Does this change alter a **model structure**? → Update `/docs/models/`
- Does this change introduce or shift **architecture**? → Update `/docs/architecture/`

### 1.2 Update Rules — Apply to Every Impacted File

For every impacted documentation file:

- **Remove or rewrite any outdated section** that no longer reflects the implementation
- **Add any missing documentation** for new classes, methods, endpoints, services, or flows
- **Verify all code examples** are accurate and runnable against the new implementation
- **Verify API contracts**: request shapes, response shapes, status codes, error formats
- **Verify permission documentation** reflects the current `permission_classes`, `has_permission`, or `has_object_permission` logic
- **Verify data flow diagrams or descriptions** are consistent with current service/view wiring

### 1.3 Structural Documentation Integrity Check

Before closing this step, verify:

- No **public API endpoint** is undocumented
- No **public service method** is undocumented
- No **custom permission class** is undocumented
- No **architectural shift** (e.g., new service layer, new async pattern, new external integration) is undocumented
- No documentation file contains **stale references** to renamed, moved, or deleted code

If documentation debt is found → **fix it now, before proceeding**.

---

## Step 2 — Change Traceability File

For **every completed prompt execution**, create a traceability file inside `/docs/changes/`.

### 2.1 File Naming Convention

```
/docs/changes/YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS_<short-descriptive-slug>.md
```

Examples:
```
/docs/changes/20240315_143022_add-user-invitation-service.md
/docs/changes/20240315_160500_refactor-payment-permission-logic.md
```

### 2.2 Required File Contents

```markdown
# Change: <Short Title>

**Date:** YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM
**Author:** AI-assisted / <developer name if known>
**Prompt Scope:** <one sentence describing what was asked>

---

## Summary
<2–4 sentences describing what was implemented or changed>

## Reason for Change
<Why this change was made — feature request, bug fix, refactor, tech debt, etc.>

## Files Modified

| File Path | Lines Modified | Nature of Change |
|-----------|---------------|-----------------|
| `app/services/user_service.py` | 45–89 | Added `invite_user()` method |
| `app/views/user_views.py` | 12–30 | Wired new service method to POST endpoint |
| `app/tests/test_user_service.py` | 1–65 | New test file for invitation service |

## Refactors Performed
- <List any refactored logic, renamed symbols, restructured modules>
- None if not applicable

## Reused Logic
- <Any existing utility, mixin, service, or helper that was deliberately reused>
- None if not applicable

## Removed Code
- <Any deleted methods, classes, files, or dead code removed>
- None if not applicable

## Related Tests Added

| Test File | Test Name | What It Covers |
|-----------|-----------|----------------|
| `app/tests/test_user_service.py` | `test_invite_user_sends_email` | Confirms email dispatch on invite |
| `app/tests/test_user_service.py` | `test_invite_user_duplicate_raises` | Validates uniqueness constraint |

## Documentation Updated
- <List every `/docs/` file that was updated as part of this change>
```

This file is **mandatory**. No prompt execution is complete without it.

---

## Step 3 — CHANGELOG Entry

### 3.1 Inspect Existing CHANGELOG Entries First

Before writing a new entry:

1. Open the `/CHANGELOG` directory
2. Read the **3 most recent entries** to understand:
   - File naming convention in use
   - Date/version format in use
   - Heading and categorization style in use
   - Level of detail expected
3. Match that exact convention in the new entry

**Never assume a format — always inspect first.**

### 3.2 Create a New Entry

Create a new file in `/CHANGELOG/` following the project's established naming pattern.

The entry must include the following categories **only if applicable**:

```markdown
## Added
- <New feature, endpoint, service, model field, command, etc.>

## Changed
- <Modified behavior, updated logic, altered response format, etc.>

## Fixed
- <Bug fix, edge case resolution, incorrect behavior corrected>

## Refactored
- <Internal restructure with no behavior change — performance, clarity, structure>

## Removed
- <Deleted endpoints, deprecated methods removed, dead code cleaned>

## Security
- <Permission changes, authentication updates, vulnerability patches>
```

### 3.3 Entry Quality Rules

- **Be concise but meaningful** — one line per item is standard; two lines maximum
- **Do not document trivial edits** (e.g., renaming a local variable, fixing a typo in a comment)
- **Aggregate related changes** from the same feature into a single entry — do not fragment
- **Reference the traceability file** if the change warrants deeper inspection:
  ```
  See: docs/changes/20240315_143022_add-user-invitation-service.md
  ```
- **Categorize accurately** — do not label a refactor as "Added" or a bug fix as "Changed"

---

## Step 4 — Completion Gate

**A feature implementation is NOT considered complete until ALL of the following are true:**

| Gate | Requirement | Status |
|------|-------------|--------|
| 1 | Tests written and passing | Required |
| 2 | Coverage thresholds enforced | Required |
| 3 | All impacted `/docs/` files updated | Required |
| 4 | No undocumented public APIs, services, or permissions | Required |
| 5 | `/docs/changes/TIMESTAMP_slug.md` traceability file created | Required |
| 6 | `/CHANGELOG/` entry written following existing convention | Required |

If **any gate is not satisfied** → the implementation is incomplete. Do not present the output as final.

Only when all 6 gates are confirmed → the feature may be considered **done**.

---

## Enforcement Reminders

- Documentation is **not optional** and is not deferred to "later"
- The traceability file is a **first-class deliverable**, not an afterthought
- CHANGELOG entries must **match the existing project's formatting** — always inspect before writing
- Any documentation debt discovered during this phase **must be resolved** before finalizing
- This rule applies to **all Django backend changes** regardless of scope — from small service methods to full feature modules
